"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Mark chapters 15–16
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-mark-15-16.py

Christological focus for this range:
- Ch 15: The Passion as the fulcrum of all Christology — Isaiah 53 Servant fulfilled,
  Psalm 22 enacted verse by verse, Psalm 69 cited, the rending of the temple curtain,
  the centurion's confession as the Gospel's climactic human declaration
- Ch 16: The resurrection as vindication and commissioning — Isaiah 35 restoration
  signs completed, the Great Commission, the Ascension and Psalm 110:1 enthronement
- Mark 15:28 and 16:9-20 (Long Ending) are textually absent from best manuscripts;
  entries note this and focus on what is Christologically established in the authentic text
- The entire Passion is read through Psalm 22 (abandonment that moves to vindication)
  and Isaiah 52:13-53:12 (Servant who suffers for the many's justification)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK = {
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>A direct fulfillment of the passion predictions: "the chief priests, with the elders, the teachers of the law and the whole Sanhedrin, made their plans. So they bound Jesus, led him away and handed him over to Pilate." Three times Jesus had predicted this (8:31, 9:31, 10:33): delivered to the chief priests, condemned to death, handed to the Gentiles. Each detail is now enacted with precision. The deliberate, planned nature of the proceedings (they "made their plans") underlines that the Passion is not a tragic accident but the fulfillment of both divine purpose and prophetic prediction.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A direct revelation of the kingship declared under duress: Pilate\'s question "Are you the king of the Jews?" and Jesus\'s "You say so" — the title that Pilate intends as mockery will be posted above the cross (v.26). The irony runs through the entire trial: the charge is "king of the Jews"; the charge is true; it is the truest thing said in the proceedings. Daniel 7:13-14 promised the Son of Man receiving "authority, glory and sovereign power" over all nations; the transfer begins here, not through triumph but through the trial that leads to the cross.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Isaiah 53:7: "the chief priests accused him of many things." The Servant "was oppressed and afflicted, yet he did not open his mouth" (Isa 53:7). Jesus\'s silence before his accusers (v.5) and the accumulation of charges against him fulfill the Servant\'s pattern of being the innocent who submits to accusation without self-defense. The chief priests\' many charges cannot be answered within the trial because the trial is not designed to discover truth; it is designed to produce a verdict already determined.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A theme of Christ submitting to unjust process as the Servant: Pilate\'s question "Aren\'t you going to answer?" invites Jesus to defend himself within the Roman system. The invitation is genuine; Pilate knows the charges are motivated by self-interest (v.10). But Jesus\'s silence is the silence of the one who has chosen the path of the cross, not the silence of the powerless. He who silenced storms (4:39) and demons (1:25) silences himself before his accusers, fulfilling the pattern of Isaiah\'s Servant led to slaughter without opening his mouth.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Isaiah 53:7: "Jesus still made no reply, and Pilate was amazed." The Servant\'s silence — so striking that Pilate marvels — is the chosen silence of the one who could call ten thousand angels (Matt 26:53) but does not. The amazement (<em>thaumazein</em>) of Pilate before Jesus\'s silence is the pagan ruler\'s involuntary recognition that something extraordinary is happening: a man in mortal danger who is not desperate. The silence is itself a form of authority — the authority of one who has accepted the cup (14:36) and will not retreat from it.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A theme of divine providence working through Barabbas: the custom of releasing a prisoner at Passover creates the mechanism for the substitution. The one guilty of murder and insurrection is released; the innocent is condemned. This is the gospel in miniature: the guilty go free; the innocent bears their sentence. Barabbas ("son of the father") goes free because the true Son of the Father goes to the cross in his place. The substitution is not allegorical; it is the literal enactment of Isaiah 53:6: "the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all."</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct type of substitutionary atonement: Barabbas — imprisoned for murder and insurrection, deserving death — is the one who goes free because another takes his place. Every human being is Barabbas: "the guilty go unpunished" not by injustice but because "the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all" (Isa 53:6). The name Barabbas (bar = son, abba = father) is the Gospel\'s signature irony: the "son of the father" is released when the actual Son of the Father is condemned. The substitution accomplished historically in Jerusalem is the substitution accomplished redemptively on the cross.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A theme of the crowd\'s role in the Passion — the people whom Jesus came to save participating in the machinery of his condemnation: the crowd requests the Passover release that will result in Barabbas going free and Jesus condemned. The crowd is not uniquely evil; they are acting within the system the chief priests are manipulating (v.11). The passion narrative consistently spreads responsibility: priests, disciples (betrayal, denial), crowd, Pilate all participate. "We all, like sheep, have gone astray" (Isa 53:6) — the Servant\'s death involves all, because it is for all.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A theme of Pilate recognizing Jesus\'s innocence without acting on it: "Do you want me to release to you the king of the Jews?" — Pilate\'s offer reflects his genuine belief that releasing Jesus is the just outcome (v.10: he knew the chief priests\' motive was envy). The title "king of the Jews" is simultaneously the Roman charge and the truth. The justice Pilate knows he should do (release the innocent king) he will fail to do, bowing instead to political pressure. His failure to do justice is the mechanism through which the divine justice that requires the cross is accomplished.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of the Servant condemned for the envy of those he came to serve: "Pilate knew it was out of self-interest that the chief priests had handed Jesus over to him." The word <em>phthonon</em> (envy, self-interest) names the human motive behind the crucifixion. Isaiah 53:3 says the Servant was "despised and rejected by mankind." The rejection is not rational (there is no charge that holds) but emotional-political: he threatens the established order. The one who came to bless his own (John 1:11: "his own did not receive him") is condemned by the envy of the very leaders who should have welcomed him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A theme of the religious establishment actively working against Christ: "the chief priests stirred up the crowd to have Pilate release Barabbas instead." The active manipulation of the crowd by the chief priests is the corruption of the shepherd role that Ezekiel 34 condemns — the shepherds who exploit rather than protect the flock. Here the shepherds of Israel drive the flock to demand the death of the true shepherd (v.34 of ch.6: "like sheep without a shepherd"). The irony is complete: the temple authorities, in trying to protect the temple from Christ, fulfill the prophecy of Isaiah 53 that identifies the Servant\'s death as God\'s purpose.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme of Pilate abdicating judicial responsibility: "What shall I do, then, with the one you call the king of the Jews?" — by asking the crowd, Pilate transfers the decision to the mob. The judicial process has collapsed into political theater: the judge has decided the accused is innocent (v.10, 14) and still proceeds to ask the accusers what he should do. The abdication of justice is the historical mechanism by which God\'s redemptive purpose is accomplished — as Peter will declare at Pentecost: "This man was handed over to you by God\'s deliberate plan and foreknowledge; and you, with the help of wicked men, put him to death" (Acts 2:23).</p>',
    "13": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Isaiah 53:8-9 and Psalm 22:6-8: "Crucify him!" — the crowd demands the most shameful form of Roman execution for one who has done no wrong. Isaiah 53:8: "By oppression and judgment he was taken away." Psalm 22:6-8: "I am a worm and not a man, scorned by everyone, despised by the people. All who see me mock me; they hurl insults, shaking their heads." The cry of the crowd is the fulfillment of these prophetic pictures of the Servant/righteous sufferer — not by coincidence but by divine design, so that the one who suffers can be identified as the one the scriptures describe.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s innocence established by his own judge: "What crime has he committed?" — Pilate\'s three-times-repeated protest of innocence (Luke 23:4,14,22; cf. here) establishes the legal record: Jesus was condemned by a judge who found him guilty of nothing. The innocence is theologically essential: "Christ died for sins once for all, the righteous for the unrighteous, to bring you to God" (1 Pet 3:18). The substitutionary atonement requires the substitute to be without fault — Pilate\'s repeated protests are the pagan governor\'s unwitting testimony to the sinlessness of the sacrificial Lamb.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Isaiah 53:5 and the passion prediction of 10:34: "He had Jesus flogged, and handed him over to be crucified." Isaiah 53:5: "by his wounds we are healed" — the flogging is the infliction of the wounds that Isaiah said would be for our healing. Jesus\'s third passion prediction (10:34) specified "they will flog him and kill him." The precision of fulfillment at every stage of the Passion is Mark\'s sustained argument: this is not a tragic accident; it is the Servant\'s mission accomplished through the precise instruments that scripture anticipated.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A theme of the Roman imperial power enacting judgment on the one who is actually Lord: the soldiers of the Praetorium (representing the full might of Roman imperial authority) assemble to mock the king. The irony is the gospel\'s sustained irony in the Passion: the ones who dress him as a mock king are dressing the actual king. The Praetorium becomes the site of the ultimate Christological revelation: the entire apparatus of Roman imperial power condemns and mocks the one before whom every knee will bow (Phil 2:10-11), not knowing what they are doing.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A direct type of royal enthronement in mockery: the purple robe and crown of thorns are the regalia of a mock coronation. They are simultaneously a mockery and an enactment: the one they dress as king is the king. The crown of thorns reverses the curse of Genesis 3:18 ("thorns and thistles it will produce for you") — the one who bears the thorns of the curse on his head takes the curse that humanity earned. The robe of purple is the color of royalty; it is placed on the one who is royalty in the act of mocking him.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation of the world\'s worship of its king in inversion: "Hail, king of the Jews!" — the acclamation is a parody of "Ave Caesar" and simultaneously the truest thing the soldiers say. The one they mock is the king; the acclamation they speak in contempt is the confession the church makes in faith. Philippians 2:11 — "every tongue acknowledge that Jesus Christ is Lord" — will be the final version of what the soldiers say in mockery. The soldiers\' words are ironically true; the church\'s words are sincerely true; the content is the same.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Isaiah 50:6: "I offered my back to those who beat me, my cheeks to those who pulled out my beard; I did not hide my face from mocking and spitting." The striking, spitting, and mock homage enacted by the soldiers fulfill in detail what Isaiah 50:6 described for the Servant. The Servant\'s willingness to offer his face to the strikers — not hiding, not fleeing — is the posture that Jesus maintains throughout the Passion: he does not retreat from the cup (14:36) or the cross. The submission is not weakness but the chosen path of redemption.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A theme of the cross as the final stripping: the purple robe removed and his own clothes restored before the procession to Golgotha. The soldiers will divide his clothes (v.24), fulfilling Psalm 22:18 — the complete stripping of the one who "became poor so that you through his poverty might become rich" (2 Cor 8:9). The return of his own clothes for the walk to Golgotha is the final identification: this is the man, the specific person, Jesus of Nazareth, the carpenter\'s son, the teacher from Galilee, walking to his own execution in his own clothes.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A theme of the cross borne by one who represents the nations bearing Christ\'s burden: Simon of Cyrene, a Diaspora Jew from Africa, is compelled to carry the cross. The involuntary cross-bearer fulfills the imagery of Luke 9:23 in reverse — instead of disciples voluntarily taking up the cross, the cross falls on one who did not choose it. Simon\'s forced service becomes a type of all who are seized by the cross\'s claim: "I was found by those who did not seek me" (Rom 10:20; Isa 65:1). The cross catches people who were not looking for it.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A direct fulfillment of the site of sacrifice: Golgotha, "the place of the skull," outside the city walls — fulfilling Hebrews 13:12-13: "Jesus also suffered outside the city gate to make the people holy through his own blood. Let us, then, go to him outside the camp." The execution outside the city walls echoes Leviticus 16:27 (the Day of Atonement sacrifice burned outside the camp) — the Great High Priest offers the atoning sacrifice at the place outside where sacrificial refuse was taken. The location is the fulfillment of the atonement typology.</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of Christ choosing to drink the cup of suffering without anesthesia: "they offered him wine mixed with myrrh, but he did not take it." In Gethsemane he had prayed "take this cup from me" but submitted: "not what I will, but what you will" (14:36). Now he refuses the cup of numbing — he will drink the cup of God\'s wrath fully conscious, fully present, without dulling the experience. The cross is not endured in a medicated half-consciousness; it is the fully deliberate, fully experienced suffering of the one who "for the joy set before him endured the cross" (Heb 12:2).</p>',
    "24": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Psalm 22:18: "they crucified him. Dividing up his clothes, they cast lots to see what each would get." Psalm 22:18: "They divide my clothes among them and cast lots for my garment." The crucifixion itself and the division of his garments are presented together — the Psalm that begins with the cry of dereliction (v.34: "My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?") is being enacted verse by verse around the cross. The Passion is the living performance of Psalm 22, and the performance vindicates the Psalm\'s trajectory: abandonment leads to vindication.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A theme of the cross as the center of time: "nine in the morning when they crucified him." The third hour marks the beginning of the three-hour structure of the Passion\'s climax — third hour (crucifixion), sixth hour (darkness), ninth hour (death). The cross is the central event of history around which time is now structured. The early church will understand the hours of the Passion liturgically; the third, sixth, and ninth hours of prayer (Acts 2:15, 3:1, 10:3) are calibrated to the hours of the cross. Time itself is marked by the one who died at the ninth hour.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A direct revelation of the charge that is simultaneously the truth: "THE KING OF THE JEWS." The titulus posted above the cross is Rome\'s declaration of the crime — claiming an unauthorized kingship. It is simultaneously the most accurate thing posted at the execution of any criminal in history: the one who hangs here is the king. The irony of the Passion reaches its literal peak in the written charge: the political mockery is the theological truth. "The rulers of this age... crucified the Lord of glory" (1 Cor 2:8) — not knowing they were doing exactly what the title announced.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Isaiah 53:12: "they crucified two rebels with him, one on his right and one on his left." Isaiah 53:12: "he was numbered with the transgressors." The two crucified rebels flanking Jesus fulfill the Servant\'s identification with sinners — not merely symbolic proximity but actual placement in the midst of those whose guilt he is bearing. The positions "on his right and on his left" echo James and John\'s request (10:37), making the two rebels the occupants of the positions of honor in Christ\'s kingdom — the cross is his enthronement, and the criminals are his court.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Mark 15:28 ("And the scripture was fulfilled that says, \'He was numbered with the transgressors\'") is absent from the earliest manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and is a scribal interpolation from Luke 22:37. The verse is not part of Mark\'s original Gospel. The Isaiah 53:12 fulfillment in v.27 (two rebels flanking Jesus) is real and present in the narrative whether or not v.28 is included — the scripture is fulfilled in the event, not merely in an editorial note about it.</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Psalm 22:7-8: "those who passed by hurled insults at him, shaking their heads and saying, \'So! You who are going to destroy the temple and build it in three days, come down from the cross and save yourself!\'" Psalm 22:7-8: "All who see me mock me; they hurl insults, shaking their heads: \'He trusts in the LORD; let the LORD rescue him. Let him deliver him, since he delights in him.\'" The mockery of passersby is not merely cruel irony but scriptural fulfillment — the one who is the righteous sufferer of Psalm 22 is identified by the specific form of his suffering.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of the cross as the ultimate test of the Christological claim: "come down from the cross and save yourself!" The demand for a sign of salvation by avoiding death is the ultimate inversion of the gospel: the sign of salvation is the cross, not the avoidance of it. The salvation Jesus came to accomplish is accomplished precisely by not coming down — by remaining on the cross until "it is finished" (John 19:30). The mockers set the condition for belief that, if Jesus met it, would falsify the atonement. The one who saves others cannot save himself from this cross without abandoning the others.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of the involuntary testimony of Christ\'s enemies: "He saved others, but he can\'t save himself!" The chief priests and scribes, in their mockery, speak the theological truth of the atonement. He saved others — this they acknowledge. He cannot save himself and save the others — this is the logic of substitutionary atonement. The one who bears the sins of many cannot simultaneously spare himself from the consequences. The mockers do not understand what they are saying; what they say is more true than they know. The gospel is preached at the foot of the cross by those who intend only contempt.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of the world demanding the wrong kind of Messiah at the moment when the right kind is accomplishing salvation: "Let this Messiah, this king of Israel, come down now from the cross, that we may see and believe." The condition they set for faith is exactly what would destroy the basis of faith: a Messiah who avoids the cross has not accomplished the atonement. The two crucified rebels join the mockery — and yet Luke 23:42 records that one of them turns from mockery to faith before the end: "Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom." Faith is possible even from the cross, even in the last hour.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of cosmic darkness as the sign of God\'s judgment: "at noon, darkness came over the whole land until three in the afternoon." Amos 8:9: "In that day, declares the Lord GOD, I will make the sun go down at noon and darken the earth in broad daylight." The darkness is the sign of the Day of the LORD — the day of divine judgment — falling on the cross. The light of the world is being put out, and the cosmos responds with darkness. The three hours of midday darkness are the hours when God\'s wrath for human sin falls on his Son — the darkest hours in history, when the sun turns its face from what it cannot look upon.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A theme of prophetic misidentification at the cross: bystanders mistake "Eloi" (my God) for "Elijah" (my God is Yahweh). The mishearing is ironic: Jesus has already identified John the Baptist as the Elijah who was to come (9:13). The crowd looks for Elijah to come and rescue the prophet — the final messianic rescue fantasy. But no rescue from the cross is coming, because the cross is not the failure of Christ\'s mission but its fulfillment. Elijah was already sent; he already came; he already died before Jesus; now the one Elijah announced is completing his mission.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Psalm 69:21: "someone ran, filled a sponge with wine vinegar, put it on a staff, and offered it to Jesus to drink." Psalm 69:21: "They put gall in my food and gave me vinegar for my thirst." The Psalm of the righteous sufferer who cries to God from humiliation — "I am a stranger to my own family" (Ps 69:8), "those who hate me without reason outnumber the hairs of my head" (Ps 69:4) — reaches its bitter detail in the vinegar offered at the cross. Like Psalm 22, Psalm 69 is being enacted at Golgotha, identifying Jesus as the one these Psalms describe.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A direct revelation of the death of Christ: "with a loud cry, Jesus breathed his last." The loud cry is the final act of the one who chose to die — not the fading away of exhaustion but a final declaration (Luke: "Father, into your hands I commit my spirit"; John: "It is finished"). The cross is not something that happened to Jesus passively; it is the culmination of a mission he pursued with his eyes open. "No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord" (John 10:18). The loud cry at death is the cry of one who has completed what he came to do.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A direct revelation of the atonement\'s completion: the temple curtain torn from top to bottom — the act of God dividing the barrier between himself and humanity. The veil before the Holy of Holies (Exod 26:31-33) was the physical marker of the inaccessibility of God\'s presence to the unclean — the way was not yet opened (Heb 9:8). At the moment of Christ\'s death, "we have confidence to enter the Most Holy Place by the blood of Jesus, by a new and living way opened for us through the curtain, that is, his body" (Heb 10:19-20). The torn curtain is the opened way, accomplished by the torn body of the one who is both priest and sacrifice.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of the women as faithful witnesses when the male disciples had fled: Mary Magdalene, Mary the mother of James and Joseph, and Salome watch from a distance. In Gethsemane, "everyone deserted him and fled" (14:50). But the women remain — watching from a distance, remaining present through the horror. Their faithfulness at the cross becomes the qualification for the resurrection commission (16:1-8). The last witnesses to the cross are the first witnesses to the empty tomb; the continuity of their testimony is the link between the death and the resurrection in Mark\'s account.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of the female disciples\' faithfulness throughout the Galilean ministry: "in Galilee these women had followed him and cared for his needs." The women\'s discipleship — following and serving — mirrors the vocabulary used for the male disciples (1:18: they "followed him"). Their faithfulness from Galilee to Jerusalem and to the cross is the consistent thread. In a narrative where the male disciples boast of their loyalty and then flee, the women\'s quiet persistence without boasting is the practical demonstration of the cross-bearing discipleship Jesus had called for (8:34). They take up the cross of presence at Golgotha when others cannot.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A theme of providential timing: Preparation Day (the Friday before the Sabbath) creates urgency — burial must happen before sunset, before the Sabbath begins. The urgency is the mechanism through which the burial is accomplished quickly and carefully, fulfilling Isaiah 53:9: "he was assigned a grave with the wicked, and with the rich in his death." Joseph of Arimathea\'s intervention provides the rich man\'s tomb (v.46). The timing of the Passover week — Preparation Day, Sabbath, first day of the week — becomes the timetable of the Passion: crucifixion, burial, resurrection.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of the unlikely disciple whose courage the apostles lacked: Joseph of Arimathea, "a prominent member of the Council, who was himself waiting for the kingdom of God, went boldly to Pilate and asked for Jesus\' body." A member of the Sanhedrin that condemned Jesus now buries him — the reversal of the condemnation by a member of the condemning body. His "waiting for the kingdom of God" is the same posture as Simeon (Luke 2:25) and Anna (Luke 2:37) — the faithful remnant of Israel who recognize in Jesus the fulfillment of their waiting. The boldness Joseph shows before Pilate is what the disciples lacked at the arrest.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A revelation of the official confirmation of Christ\'s death: Pilate "was surprised to hear that he was already dead" and summoned the centurion to confirm it. The centurion\'s official testimony (v.45) establishes the death by the most authoritative witness available in the Roman system — the military officer who supervised the execution. The official confirmation serves the gospel\'s historical apologetic: the resurrection claim cannot be dismissed as revival from a faint; the death was confirmed by Roman military authority. Pilate\'s surprise (six hours was fast) and the centurion\'s confirmation together close the case on the death.</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of the body released for burial — the death confirmed, the gift given: Pilate gives the body to Joseph. The release of the body of the crucified Servant for honorable burial fulfills Isaiah 53:9: "he was assigned a grave with the wicked, and with the rich in his death." The body of the one who "had no place to lay his head" (Luke 9:58) during his ministry is given a rich man\'s tomb at his death — the provision of the Father for the Servant who completed his mission. The gift of burial to the unjustly executed is the last act of justice in a Passion full of injustice.</p>',
    "46": '<p>A direct type of the resurrection to come: the body wrapped in linen, placed in a rock-cut tomb, sealed with a stone. The burial is the threshold between the cross and the resurrection — the body placed in the tomb with care and witnesses (v.47) is the same body that will leave the tomb on the third day. The burial confirms the death (the resurrection is from actual death, not from apparent death) and establishes the continuity between the crucified body and the risen body. "He who raised Christ from the dead will also give life to your mortal bodies through his Spirit" (Rom 8:11).</p>',
    "47": '<p>A revelation of the women\'s continuous witness linking cross to resurrection: "Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of Joseph saw where he was laid." They witnessed the death (v.40) and now the burial — and will return to find the tomb empty (16:1-8). Their unbroken chain of witness is the historical foundation for the resurrection testimony: they can testify that the tomb in which they now see the body laid is the same tomb they will find empty. No confusion of tombs, no mistake about the location — the same women, the same tomb, three days apart. This is the eyewitness chain that the resurrection proclamation rests on.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "1": '<p>A theme of faithful love expressed in the face of death: the women buy spices "so that they might go to anoint Jesus\' body." They go to honor a dead man — they have no expectation of resurrection despite his three predictions of it (8:31, 9:31, 10:34). Their love does not require hope to act; they serve even in grief. The anointing intention echoes the woman at Bethany (14:8) who "anointed my body beforehand for burial" — the one who anointed him before the cross and the ones who come to anoint him after it are united in the same act of devoted service to the one whose death they mourn.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of the resurrection on the first day of the week — the dawn of the new creation: "very early on the first day of the week, just after sunrise." The timing is cosmic: the same phrase that begins Genesis 1 ("the beginning," "God said, \'Let there be light\'") finds its echo in the dawn of the first day of the week when the Light of the world rises from the dead. The first day of the week becomes the Lord\'s Day for the church precisely because of what happens at this sunrise. The resurrection is the beginning of the new creation (2 Cor 5:17; Rev 21:5).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A theme of human inability encountering divine action: "Who will roll the stone away from the entrance of the tomb?" — the women\'s question is the question of all who come to Christ with a need that exceeds their capacity to solve. The stone is too heavy; they cannot move it. They come anyway, asking the practical question on the road. The gospel consistently meets people at the point of their acknowledged inability: the stone that seals them from Christ has already been rolled away when they arrive. The obstacle they feared is gone before they get there.</p>',
    "4": '<p>A revelation of divine action preceding human arrival: "the stone, which was very large, had been rolled away." The rolling of the stone is not narrated in Mark (contrast Matt 28:2); Mark simply records the discovery — the stone is already moved when the women arrive. The resurrection does not wait for human witnesses or human assistance. God acted in the darkness, while the women slept, before anyone came to observe. The resurrection is a divine act that human beings discover, not one they facilitate or witness in its occurrence. They arrive to find what has already happened.</p>',
    "5": '<p>A revelation of the angelic announcement at the empty tomb: "a young man dressed in a white robe sitting on the right side." The messenger in white at the right side — the position of honor and authority — is the divine attestation of the resurrection. The women\'s alarm (<em>exethambēthēsan</em>) is the appropriate response to an encounter with the numinous — the same reaction as at the transfiguration (9:6: <em>ekphoboi</em>). The empty tomb alone might be ambiguous (the body removed, an unknown explanation); the messenger clarifies what the empty tomb means: the crucified one is risen.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A direct revelation of Christ\'s forgiveness and restoration of Peter: "go, tell his disciples and Peter." Peter\'s specific naming in the resurrection announcement is the Good Shepherd coming after the one lost sheep of the inner circle. Peter had denied Christ three times (14:66-72) and "went outside and wept bitterly" (Luke 22:62). The resurrection\'s first pastoral act is to include by name the one who excluded himself by his failure. The risen Christ\'s first message is not condemnation of the denier but a specific summons. The "and Peter" is grace visible in two words.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of the resurrection as the mystery that exceeds immediate comprehension: "trembling and bewildered, the women went out and fled from the tomb. They said nothing to anyone, because they were afraid." The original ending of Mark does not conclude with triumphant proclamation but with fear and silence — the overwhelmed response to an encounter with the resurrection. The fear (<em>ephobounto gar</em>) is not unbelief but awe — the appropriate initial response to something that exceeds all categories. The gospel does not end here, because the reader now holds the news the women could not speak. The loop is open; the story continues in the one who reads it.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The Long Ending (16:9-20) is absent from the oldest Greek manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and most early witnesses; it is a second-century addition to provide a fuller conclusion. The tradition it contains — Mary Magdalene\'s appearance (v.9), the two disciples on the road (v.12), the commissioning (v.15-16), the ascension (v.19) — draws on authentic resurrection tradition attested in Luke and John. The Christological content is not invented; the question is only whether Mark wrote these verses. The risen Christ who appears, commissions, and ascends is the same one whose death and burial Mark has narrated.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A theme of the risen Christ\'s testimony reaching grieving disciples: Mary Magdalene goes and tells those "mourning and weeping" — the community of disciples in the aftermath of the crucifixion, grief-stricken and without hope. The resurrection testimony reaches the grief first: before any theological instruction, before any appearance to the group, the news of the risen Christ reaches those who mourn. The gospel is always good news to those in grief — the announcement that the one who was dead is alive is the answer to the mourning that death produces.</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of the disciples\' initial disbelief as the record of genuine historical testimony: "they did not believe it." The disciples\' disbelief of Mary Magdalene\'s testimony is the NT\'s consistent account of the resurrection\'s initial reception (Luke 24:11: "their words seemed to them like nonsense"). The disbelief is not a failure of the witnesses but a confirmation of the testimony\'s credibility: these are not credulous enthusiasts who believe whatever they hope for. The resurrection overcame systematic skepticism — which is why the faith that results from it is faith in something that was confirmed against initial resistance.</p>',
    "12": '<p>A theme of the risen Christ appearing in unexpected form: "Jesus appeared in a different form to two of them while they were walking in the country" — corresponding to the Emmaus road (Luke 24:13-35). The unrecognized risen Christ walking with those who do not recognize him is the pattern of resurrection appearances: he is the same person and a different person, the same body and a transformed body. The resurrection body is not the resuscitation of a corpse but the transformation of the body that was buried. "We shall be like him, for we shall see him as he is" (1 John 3:2) — the transformation awaiting believers is the transformation already enacted in Christ.</p>',
    "13": '<p>A theme of the accumulation of resurrection testimony before belief breaks through: the two report to the rest; the rest do not believe them. Three testimony-chains fail before the appearance to the Eleven (v.14) breaks the pattern of disbelief. The accumulation of failed testimonies is historically significant: it means the resurrection faith was not adopted enthusiastically or credulously but was forced on people who resisted it. "He presented himself alive after his suffering by many convincing proofs" (Acts 1:3) — the proofs were necessary because the disciples\' initial disposition was disbelief, not credulity.</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of Christ confronting and overcoming the hardened hearts of his disciples with his own presence: "Later Jesus appeared to the Eleven as they were eating; he rebuked them for their lack of faith and their stubborn refusal to believe." The hardened heart (<em>sklērokardia</em>) diagnosed throughout Mark (6:52, 8:17, 10:5) is the final obstacle that the resurrection appearance itself overcomes. The rebuke is grace: he appears to them, he confronts their unbelief, he commissions them. The disciples who failed to understand the feedings, the transfiguration, and the passion predictions are now confronted with the risen Lord who will not leave them in their failure.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A direct revelation of the Great Commission as the risen Christ extending his own mission: "Go into all the world and preach the gospel to all creation." The mission that began in Galilee (1:14-15: "Jesus went into Galilee, proclaiming the good news of God... \'Repent and believe the good news!\'") now extends to "all creation." The one who moved between Jewish and Gentile territory throughout his ministry (5:1, 7:24, 7:31) now commissions the movement to "all the world." The Gentile mission that was anticipated in the Gerasene demoniac (5:19-20) and the Syrophoenician woman (7:29) is now formally authorized by the risen Christ.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A direct revelation of salvation through faith in the risen Christ: "whoever believes and is baptized will be saved, but whoever does not believe will be condemned." The structure of salvation — believing the gospel and being baptized as its public expression — is the response the risen Christ calls for from the world he is sending his disciples to. The condemnation falls on unbelief (not on unbaptized status), because it is faith in the crucified and risen Christ that justifies (Rom 3:26). The one who died as a ransom for many (10:45) now calls the many to receive that ransom through faith.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of Christ\'s authority extending through his representatives by signs: "in my name they will drive out demons; they will speak in new tongues." The apostolic signs are extensions of Christ\'s own ministry (exorcism: 1:25, 3:11, 5:8; new tongues: Acts 2:4). "In my name" is the authorization: the representatives act not by their own authority but by the authority of the one who sends them. Acts 3:6 illustrates this: "in the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, walk" — Peter acts as the agent of the absent-yet-present Christ. The signs authenticate the agents by the authority of the one whose name they invoke.</p>',
    "18": '<p>A theme of the supernatural protection of Christ\'s witnesses in hostile environments: "they will pick up snakes; when they drink deadly poison, it will not hurt them." Acts 28:3-6 records the fulfillment of the snake promise with Paul on Malta — the viper bite that produces no harm. The promise is not a license for recklessness but an assurance that the mission Christ sends his people on will not be frustrated by the dangers of the mission field. The healing by hand-laying (Acts 3:7, 9:17, 28:8) continues the same pattern: the hands that were extended on the cross extend healing through those who bear his name.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A direct fulfillment of Psalm 110:1: "after the Lord Jesus had spoken to them, he was taken up into heaven and he sat at the right hand of God." Psalm 110:1: "The LORD says to my lord: \'Sit at my right hand until I make your enemies a footstool for your feet.\'" Jesus had cited this Psalm at his trial (14:62: "you will see the Son of Man sitting at the right hand of the Mighty One") as the Christological claim that the Sanhedrin called blasphemy. The Ascension and session at the right hand is the vindication of that claim. The one they condemned for claiming to sit at God\'s right hand now sits at God\'s right hand. The trial\'s verdict is reversed.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A direct revelation of the risen Christ continuing his mission through his church: "the Lord worked with them and confirmed his word by the signs that accompanied it." The missionary activity of Acts is the continuation of the Gospel of Mark: the disciples go out; the Lord works with them; the word is confirmed by signs. Mark\'s Gospel opens with "the beginning of the gospel of Jesus Christ" (1:1) — and it ends without a true ending because the gospel does not end. The story Mark begins continues in Acts, in the church, in the proclamation of every generation, until the one who ascended to the Father\'s right hand returns.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-christ chs 15-16: {total} verses total written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
